                  		Related Deloitte Insights
                  	



Managing Risk in an Age of Social Media

                          Social media channels provide many opportunities for brands, but they also pose significant threats. By enlisting support from chief marketing officers (CMOs), knowing which questions to ask, developing plans and leveraging available tools, board members may be better prepared to help their organizations manage risk in the digital environment. Learn what steps CMOs can take to help boards in these efforts and the questions boards can pose to CMOs and other senior executives to help clarify brand positioning and mitigate potential damage on social media.
                        



PCAOB Adopts Changes to the Auditor’s Report

                          The Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (PCAOB) adopted a new auditing standard aimed at increasing the informational value, usefulness and relevance of the auditor’s report. The standard retains the PCAOB’s current pass/fail opinion of the existing auditor’s report, and includes several significant modifications, including enhanced descriptions of the auditor’s roles and responsibilities, communication of critical audit matters and disclosure of auditor tenure. Learn what other key changes are part of the new standard and on what areas of the standard management and boards might want to focus.
                        



Strategic Shifts Can Bring CFO Recruiting and Succession Challenges

                          Rising expectations from CEOs and boards for CFOs to play a greater part as business leaders, even leading company-wide transformations, is producing significant ripple effects on finance talent development, succession planning and recruitment, according to Bryan Proctor, head of the Financial Officer Center of Expertise at Korn Ferry. Mr. Proctor describes how some organizations are adapting, such as by seeking out “superstar No. 2s”—executives with both a breadth of experience in leading change and the necessary depth in finance to support transformations—and developing rigorous succession planning discipline.
                        

















                  		Views & Analysis
                  	



Creating Value Through Compliance Modernization

                          The foundational role of compliance is to prevent, detect, respond to and remediate risk. A modernized compliance function, however, can shift beyond its traditional role of value protection toward value creation. Modernizing the function entails taking a broad view of the way compliance is governed, how oversight processes are designed and executed, and how technology and analytics can be utilized to provide insight and value. It also takes into account the number and nature of connection points to other parts of the risk management organization or to the business.
                        



How Chief Compliance Officers Can Make an Immediate Impact

                          Although chief compliance officers (CCOs) are commonplace in large, heavily regulated industries, getting a seat at the highest levels of an organization isn’t always a given. CCOs, however, can be important contributors to their organizations’ strategic agendas, according to Keith Darcy, independent senior advisor to Deloitte & Touche LLP and former executive director of the Ethics & Compliance Officer Association; and Maureen Mohlenkamp, a Deloitte Risk and Financial Advisory principal at Deloitte & Touche LLP, who both conduct transition labs for incoming CCOs. They discuss why a CCO’s first 180 days is a critical window for setting an agenda, and the importance of strategic alignment at the enterprise level.
                        



Strengthening Government Contract Compliance

                          Government contract work is highly regulated, and government audits of a contractor’s finances, processes and controls can help tighten procedures, but also reveal issues that may expose organizations to compliance and business risks. Understand what contractors can expect from a government audit and some common compliance challenges. Further, learn practical steps executives can take to address contract risk and compliance issues, including creating a culture of compliance and open communication and acquiring the tools that allow organizations to identify anomalies and trends.
                        









                  		Editor's Choice
                  	



Gaining Control of Earnings Calls

                          In the eleventh hour before an earnings call many C-suite executives can be found combing through metrics, spreadsheet data and the output from analytical models, searching for insights that could help them communicate to investors and analysts a narrative about performance. Learn how streamlining the information production process on the front end may help executives in gaining insights to manage the business and in crafting a more effective message to the investment community. Also, understand how focusing on what drives the business when creating a narrative can create a feedback loop that operationalizes the organization’s strategy.
                        



Risk Managers Less Confident About Newer Risks, Cybersecurity: Global Survey

                          Risk management executives are less confident about their organization’s ability to combat newer risks, such as model risk and third-party risks, while cybersecurity remains an area of significant concern, according to the 10th edition of Deloitte’s Global Risk Management survey. The survey findings, which comprise responses from 77 financial services institutions around the world, indicate that areas of increasing maturity in risk management programs include more active board oversight and increased adoption of the CRO position. Nevertheless, risk management programs may need to increase their ability to anticipate and respond flexibly to new regulatory and business developments.
                        



Auto Sector Compliance: Weighing the Benefits of ISO Anti-Bribery Guidance

                          The anti-bribery management standards issued by the Geneva-based International Organization for Standardization (ISO) provide automotive companies, as well as global organizations in other sectors, with new guidance and tools that could potentially help mitigate the risks and costs of noncompliance with anti-bribery laws. Learn about the global nature of the new ISO guidance, as well as other considerations for any organization considering incorporating it into their ethics and compliance program.
                        







              		About Deloitte Insights
              	

Deloitte’s Insights for C-suite executives and board members provide information and resources to help address the challenges of managing risk for both value creation and protection, as well as increasing compliance requirements.
















































































